Pop a wide bottomed #saucepan{} on medium heat and add a splash of @oil{}. Add the @spiced pork sausages{8} and cook for ~{5-7%minutes}, turning frequently to make sure they brown evenly.

While your sausages brown get on with the rest of your prep. Cut the @red onions{2} in half through the root, peel and then slice into thin half moon shapes. Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{} if you have one). Roughly chop the @coriander{2%bunches}.

Fill a #pot{} with the @water{800%ml} and bring to the boil. Stir in the @chicken stock pots{2} and make sure it is dissolved. Pour the @bulgur wheat{200%g} into a #bowl{}. Pour half your stock onto your bulgur wheat, cover with a #lid{} or #plate{} and leave to one side for ~{15%minutes}.

> The bulgur wheat will stay warm whilst you finish the rest of your meal.

When your sausages are nicely browned, add your red onion to the pan with the sausages. Cook for ~{5%minutes} until softened and then add your garlic, @smoked paprika{1%tsp} and @ground coriander{1%tsp}. Cook for a couple of mins until everything smells delicious and fragrant.

Add the @tomato puree{2%tbsp}, cook for ~{1%minute} and then add the @chopped tomatoes{2%425g cans}. Bring everything to the boil and then stir in the remaining stock, reduce the heat to medium and leave to bubble away for ~{10-15%minutes}. You want your sauce to thicken and reduce by half.

Drain the @red kidney beans{2%400g cans} into a #sieve{} or #colander{} and rinse under cold water. Remove the root from the bottom of the @spring onions{4} and then slice as thinly as possible. Zest and juice the @lemon{1}.

When your sauce has reduced by half, stir in your kidney beans and @baby spinach{1%bag}, reduce the heat to low and cook for ~{5%minutes} until your spinach has wilted and your kidney beans are piping hot.

Finish your bulgur wheat by mixing in your spring onion, half your chopped coriander and enough lemon juice and zest to taste. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if you feel it needs it.

Taste your sausage hot pot and season with salt and pepper if necessary, then stir in your remaining coriander.

Serve your sausage hot pot on top of a bed of bulgur wheat and enjoy!